threatTypes.shortTitle: Manipulate {target.Name} data in order to fake an object
shortTitleParts: data in order to fake an object
threatTypes.description: Spoofing {source.Name} data in order to let the camera think a fake object is in front of it.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Dropping a reflector in front of the car in order to cause an emergency stop.
threatTypes.recommendation: Validate target credibility on the {target.Name} via the Sensor Fusion. Introduce redundancy.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Turning functions On/Off  of the car without user interaction
threatTypes.description: Spoofing an message from {source.Name} in order to enable/disable functions of the care.g. the Lane Keep Assist.
threatTypes.attackMethod: From the {source.Name} send an on/off CAN message to the Lane Keeping ECU.
threatTypes.recommendation: Implement data validation and message authentication codes.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Another person is claiming to be the {source.Name}
shortTitleParts: Another person is claiming to be the
threatTypes.description: Another person claims to be the {source.Name} in order to execute malicious commands.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Copy the key of the driver to pretend to be the driver. Use a modified diagnostic device and connect it to the OBDII Port.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use secure authentication, like a key with a good cryptographic algorithm.

threatTypes.shortTitle: A fake HMI can send wrong signals to the driver
threatTypes.description: A fake HMI can send wrong signals to the driver, so he will react dangerously.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Replace critica signal devices of an HMI or the HMI completely
threatTypes.recommendation: Not only should the driver authenticate itself to vehicle, but also vice versa, the vehicle to the driver with a system check if it was changed.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Claiming to be a {target.Name} and therefore controlling the traffic
threatTypes.description: A gateway will be replaced or claimed to be. Therefore the whole communication of all devices connected to the gateway can be controlled.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Attach yourself to the network, copy the address of the pysical layer of your target, disconnect it and replace your device with it.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use authentication with certificates and a trustzone for the private key.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Another device which is connected to the {target.Name} is claiming to be {source.Name}
shortTitleParts: Another device which is connected to the
threatTypes.description: Another device is physically inserted, e.g. cloning the MAC adress of the target, and therefore claiming to be the {source.Name}. Then the malicious device can read but also send malicious data causing harm.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Attach yourself to the network, copy the address of the physical layer of your target, disconnect it and replace your device with it.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use authentication with certificates and a trustzone for the private key.

threatTypes.shortTitle: False firmware update sever delivers false updates
threatTypes.description: A false update server may inject malicious FW updates not only to one but to all vehicles.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Hijack the FW update server and get it under control
threatTypes.recommendation: Use authentication with certificates

threatTypes.shortTitle: False firmware store provides false firmware
threatTypes.description: A false firmware data store may provide false firmwares to the devices, so they load and behave wrong.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Replace the storage device or database with your own.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use authentication with certificates and a trustzone for the private key.

threatTypes.shortTitle: A false {source.Name} may provide wrong sensor data
threatTypes.description: A false {source.Name} may provide wrong data
threatTypes.attackMethod: Replace the device
threatTypes.recommendation: Use authentication with certificates and a trustzone for the private key.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Manipulate software configurations sent to the {target.Name}, potentially causing the car to behave differently
shortTitleParts: Manipulate software configurations sent to the
, potentially causing the car to behave differently
threatTypes.description: Tamper with software configurations sent to {target.Name}, potentially causing the car to behave differently
threatTypes.attackMethod: Update parameters via CAN bus, for example via the diagnostic port.
threatTypes.recommendation: Implement data validation and message authentication codes.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Modify data being sent to the {target.Name} while in transit
shortTitleParts: Modify data being sent to the
threatTypes.description: Tamper with data in transit sent to the {target.Name}.
threatTypes.attackMethod: MITM on the TCU for example a 3g to 2g downgrade attack, or false base station attack.
threatTypes.recommendation: Disable 2G communications, only 3G and 4G should be allowed. Use a secure communication channel between the car and the server.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Data send over {flow.Name} can be tampered with
threatTypes.description: Every Data send over a Flow can be tampered with
threatTypes.attackMethod: Gain access either to the physical network (lines) or control over one device connected to it.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use Signatures with Certificates and the private keys in special Trust Zones.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Mechanic using diagnostic line, but denies the changes
threatTypes.description: The Diagnostic Service (e.g. through ODBII Port) has extended capabilities, therefore using it should require non-repudiation
threatTypes.attackMethod: Acquire a ODBII Device, manipulate it and use it against a vehicle.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use a log when UDS is used and require authentication

threatTypes.shortTitle: Car could be tracked
threatTypes.description: Information disclosure by performing a MITM attack in order to track a car.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Downgrade or false base station attack.
threatTypes.recommendation: Encrypt communications so that passive interception cannot identify specific vehicles. Rolling/unique identifiers that change over time, to prevent tracking.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Data flow sniffing
threatTypes.description: Data flowing across [Generic Data Flow] may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. In general, as a way to compromise both integrity and availability. Severity might change depending on the attacker's access vector.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Man-in-the-middle using attack using hardware or software.
threatTypes.recommendation: Consider encrypting the data flow. For web traffic this can be achieved by using HTTPS.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Mechanic can aquire confidential information
threatTypes.description: A mechanic can aquire confidential information about the driver through the diagnostic port
threatTypes.attackMethod: Connect to Diagnostic Port and try to get as much information as possible (even restricted)
threatTypes.recommendation: Don't store user data which are not required. And if storage is necessary, limit it's access and encrypt it.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Other connected parts of a Gateway may acquire more information than allowed
threatTypes.description: If the routing is not correct, a gateway may send confidential packets to the wrong targets. Or a device may be faked and connected to the gateway.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Misbehavior of the Gateway. Or connecting to one and faking a device.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Driver may extract confidential information
threatTypes.description: A driver may extract too much information through the HMI, which should be confidential to the car alone.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Try to use the HMI to get more information; like the attack with the modified FW on a CD or USB stick, overriding the existing one after inserting it. Then store the data gained on a device or display it.
threatTypes.recommendation: Limit the use of the HMI what it can do.

threatTypes.shortTitle: CAN Bus reveals all messages to everyone on the Bus
threatTypes.description: The principle of a BUS is, that every device sees every package. Therefore a device on the BUS may read confidential messages.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Attach a device to the CAN Bus, and sniff all messages.
threatTypes.recommendation: Encrypt the data transmission; and limit the accessibility to the CAN Bus.

threatTypes.shortTitle: A TCU may reveal too much information
threatTypes.description: The TCU can be a main target for attacks, because it provides an interface for attacks over a longer range (not physical)
threatTypes.attackMethod: Attack the TCU like using weaknesses in the wireless protocols (Bluetooth, WiFi, etc.)
threatTypes.recommendation: Limit the possibilities one can do through the TCU; Use Strong passphrases; Use SSL, etc.

threatTypes.shortTitle: {flow.Name} can be attack through DOS
threatTypes.description: Nearly all Flows can be attacked through a DOS, and there are not many counter measures.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Flood a Flow with packets
threatTypes.recommendation: Use Authentication; Use a protocol, which can switch off single nodes; or set them on a ignore list.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Attempt to reflash the {source.Name} ECU in order to fully control it.
shortTitleParts: ECU in order to fully control it.
threatTypes.description: Elevation of privileges in order to gain complete control of {target.Name}.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Sending diagnostic messages to the actuator ECU then flashing a malicious firmware image.
threatTypes.recommendation: All firmware should be signed and validated to prevent malicious updates from being flashed to the ECU.

threatTypes.shortTitle: Reflash the {target.Name} firmware in order to send arbitrary CAN messages
shortTitleParts: firmware in order to send arbitrary CAN messages
threatTypes.description: Elevation of privileges in order to reflash the {target.Name} firmware.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Physically connect to the target is [TCU] and attempt to reflash the chip.
threatTypes.recommendation: All firmware should be encrypted and signed to prevent modification. There should be a secure boot process to prevent any invalid firmware from booted.

threatTypes.shortTitle: A mechanic may try do more than he should
threatTypes.description: A mechanic can try do do more than he is allowed
threatTypes.attackMethod: Exploiting the diagnostic service, e.g. doing a FW update
threatTypes.recommendation: Use capabilities and rights management

threatTypes.shortTitle: A Driver may try to do more than he should
threatTypes.description: A Driver can try to do more than he is allowed
threatTypes.attackMethod: Exploiting the HMI, e.g. doing a FW Update
threatTypes.recommendation: Use capabilities and rights management

threatTypes.shortTitle: Anyone can try to get firmware of other devices than his own
threatTypes.description: Depending on the API, the Firmware Update Server may give the users more FW, than they should, e.g. of another model.
threatTypes.attackMethod: Try to harvest all available FW on the server, e.g. through URL Manipulation. And if available, try to use false Credentials, etc.
threatTypes.recommendation: Use Authentication with Rights Management

threatTypes.shortTitle: An unauthorized process may overwrite the firmware
threatTypes.description: An unauthorized process can try to overwrite an existing firmware therefore getting control of the device
threatTypes.attackMethod: Try to use the diagnostic messages so flash a FW. Or try to do it physically
threatTypes.recommendation: Use Signature Verification so only those signed by the company may be installed. And restrict the capability to reflash a firmware to certain processes (with Authentication).
